  "name": "Morrison COU1 — CPB hemolysis credibility assessment (env-gap adversarial)",
  "description": "V&V 40 credibility assessment for CFD hemolysis prediction of the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump under cardiopulmonary bypass (CPB) conditions. COU1 evaluates whether the computational model can identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for a Class II CPB device at Model Risk Level 2. Full 13-factor assessment: 7 factors assessed (all meeting required levels), 6 factors not assessed (acceptable at MRL 2). NOTE: The CPB device is deployed in operating-theatre environments subject to temperature drift (18–26°C), electromagnetic interference from electrosurgical units and monitoring equipment, and ambient pressure variation (hypobaric transport scenarios up to 2500 m altitude). All validation experiments were conducted at 22°C, atmospheric pressure, in an electromagnetically shielded laboratory. No environmental-sensitivity study has been linked and the operating envelope does not bound these environmental parameters.",
  "assuranceLevel": "Medium",
  "bindsRequirement": "https://uofa.net/synth/req/morrison-cou1-hemolysis-rh-criterion",
  "bindsClaim": "https://uofa.net/synth/claim/morrison-cou1-cfd-hemolysis-worst-case",
  "bindsModel": "https://uofa.net/synth/model/morrison-cfd-centrifugal-pump-hemolysis-v2",
  "bindsDataset": [
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-fda-pump-experimental-piv-dataset",
    "https://uofa.net/synth/data/morrison-hemolysis-bench-validation-dataset"
  ],
  "hasContextOfUse": {
    "decisionConsequence": "High",
    "description": "A CFD model is used to evaluate the sensitivity of pump-induced hemolysis to variations in component dimensions for a centrifugal blood pump used during cardiopulmonary bypass surgery. Model influence is MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence is HIGH (incorrect tolerance decision could impact clinical hemolysis levels). Model Risk Level 2. The device is routinely operated in environments with significant temperature variation (operating theatres range 18–26°C), electromagnetic interference from co-located electrosurgical and patient-monitoring equipment, and in some transport scenarios, reduced ambient pressure (up to 2500 m altitude). These environmental factors can alter blood viscosity, sensor calibration, and pump controller behaviour in ways that may affect the hemolysis index.",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/cou/cou1-cpb",
    "intendedUse": "Use CFD to identify worst-case operating conditions for hemolysis across 5 flow-speed combinations for a Class II CPB device. Results compared against predicate device hemolysis using relative hemolysis index (RH < 1 acceptance criterion).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "name": "COU1: Cardiopulmonary bypass use (Class II)",
    "type": "ContextOfUse"
  },
  "hasValidationResult": [
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-piv-velocity-lab-22C",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "PIV velocity field comparison — laboratory at 22°C, atmospheric pressure",
      "description": "Particle image velocimetry measurements acquired in a temperature-controlled laboratory at 22 ± 0.5°C and 101.3 kPa ambient pressure. CFD velocity predictions compared against PIV data at five flow-speed operating points. Mean absolute error in axial velocity < 4%. No electromagnetic interference mitigation was applied; measurements taken in a Faraday-shielded test cell. Environmental conditions were not varied across the test matrix."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/morrison-hemolysis-bench-lab-22C",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Hemolysis index bench validation — laboratory at 22°C, atmospheric pressure",
      "description": "In-vitro hemolysis experiments conducted at 22°C and atmospheric pressure using bovine blood analogue. Relative hemolysis index RH computed from plasma-free haemoglobin measurements. CFD-predicted RH agreed with measured RH within 8% across all five operating points. All experiments performed under standard laboratory conditions; temperature, pressure, and electromagnetic environment were not varied. No environmental sensitivity study was performed and no data outside the 22°C / 101.3 kPa / shielded-lab envelope is available."
    }
  ],
